CleanPlate — Secure Roommate Chore Coordinator
==============================================

Standard library only. No pip install required.
Requires Python 3.10+.

Platform: Linux / macOS. Tested on Ubuntu 22.04.


OVERVIEW
--------

CleanPlate now runs as an interactive client session.

- Use `./cleanplate` to open the client shell.
- Type the normal structured commands inside that shell.
- Use `python3 main.py serve` to start the API server.

The client no longer expects you to run app commands directly from your OS shell.


QUICK START
-----------

  # Terminal 1: start the server
  python3 main.py serve

  # Terminal 2: open the client shell
  ./cleanplate

  cleanplate> register alice
  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> household create "42 Elm Street"
  cleanplate> household list
  cleanplate> exit


INTERACTIVE SHELL
-----------------

Open the client shell with:

  ./cleanplate

Inside the shell:

- Type `help` to see the available command tree.
- Type `exit` or `quit` to leave the shell.
- Use the same command structure each time; no wrapper aliases or flat shortcuts.

Examples:

  cleanplate> register alice
  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> whoami
  cleanplate> create household "Maple House"
  cleanplate> household create "Maple House"
  cleanplate> household join aB3xQr_kLmN
  cleanplate> create chore "Take out trash"
  cleanplate> chore create 1 "Take out trash"
  cleanplate> activity complete 4
  cleanplate> help
  cleanplate> exit

By default the client connects to http://127.0.0.1:8000.
To use a different server, set CLEANPLATE_SERVER_URL.
Client logins are terminal-scoped by default, so different terminals can stay
logged in as different users concurrently. You can also override the local
session file with CLEANPLATE_SESSION_NAME or CLEANPLATE_SESSION_PATH.


COMMAND REFERENCE
-----------------

Run these inside the `cleanplate>` prompt.

Common interactive shorthand:
  login alice
  register alice
  reset-password alice
  create household "Maple House"
  create chore "Take out trash"
  household create "Maple House"
  household join aB3xQr_kLmN
  household show 1
  chore create 1 "Take out trash"
  chore assign 4 bob
  chore list 1
  chore show 4
  activity complete 4
  activity incomplete 4
  activity audit 1

The shell also still accepts the explicit flag form when you prefer it.
For complex commands, omitted fields are prompted for interactively.

-- Identity & Access --
  register [--username <name>]
  login [--username <name>]
  reset-password [--username <name>]
  logout
  whoami

-- Household Management --
  household create        [--name "42 Elm St"]
  household join          [--code <invite_code>]
  household show          [--id <household_id>]
  household list
  household rotate-invite [--id <household_id>]
  household remove-member [--id <household_id>] [--username bob]

-- Chore Management --
  chore create     [--household <id>] [--title "Take out trash"] [--due YYYY-MM-DD] [--assign bob]
  chore assign     [--chore <id>] [--username bob]
  chore list       [--household <id>] [--status pending|complete|disputed] [--mine] [--overdue]
  chore show       [--chore <id>]
  chore reschedule [--chore <id>] --due YYYY-MM-DD

-- Activity & Completion --
  activity complete   [--chore <id>]
  activity incomplete [--chore <id>]
  activity dispute    [--chore <id>] --reason "Floor still dirty"
  activity resolve    [--complaint <id>] --outcome uphold|dismiss --note "..."
  activity audit      [--household <id>]
  activity poll


EXAMPLE WALKTHROUGH
-------------------

  # Start the server
  python3 main.py serve

  # In another terminal, open the client shell
  ./cleanplate

  cleanplate> register alice
  cleanplate> register bob

  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> create household "42 Elm Street"
  # → prints invite code, e.g. "Invite code: aB3xQr_kLmN"

  cleanplate> login bob
  cleanplate> household join aB3xQr_kLmN

  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> create chore "Vacuum living room"
  Household ID: 1
  Description (blank for none):
  Due date YYYY-MM-DD (blank for none): 2026-04-10
  Assign to username (blank for none): bob

  cleanplate> login bob
  cleanplate> activity complete 1

  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> activity dispute 1 --reason "Missed under the couch"
  cleanplate> activity resolve 1 --outcome uphold --note "Please redo"
  cleanplate> activity audit 1
  cleanplate> exit


FILE LAYOUT
-----------

  cleanplate        Shell wrapper that launches the interactive client
  main.py           Shell launcher + API server entry point
  client_cli.py     Interactive command handlers and parser wiring
  api_client.py     JSON/HTTP client helper
  api_server.py     HTTP server exposing command handlers
  db.py             SQLite schema and query helpers
  session.py        Client file session + request session scope
  auth.py           Register, login, logout, whoami
  households.py     Create, join, manage households
  chores.py         Create, assign, list chores
  activity.py       Complete, dispute, resolve, audit log
  cleanplate.db     Created automatically on first run


ARCHITECTURE
------------

Client:
  - `./cleanplate` opens a persistent interactive shell
  - commands are parsed locally, then sent to the HTTP server
  - session state is stored locally so login persists between commands

Server:
  - `python3 main.py serve`
  - runs the business logic modules and owns all database access

Database:
  - SQLite remains on the server side only


SECURITY NOTES
--------------

Passwords:
  - hashed with scrypt
  - parameters follow the current project settings in `auth.py`
  - password strength checks reject common, sequential, and weak values

Audit log:
  - HMAC-SHA256 chained
  - `verify_chain()` detects tampering

Session:
  - stored in `~/.cleanplate_session`
  - cleared on logout

Authorization:
  - role checks happen on sensitive commands, not just at login

Multi-household support:
  - a single user account can belong to multiple households at the same time
  - membership is tracked per `(user_id, household_id)`
